msgid "1661611924992392 ;"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:600
msgid "The raw data can be preprocessed in R: Nanoseconds in Epoch time can be converted to date-time with the command `as.POSIXct(<NANOSECONDS>/1000000, origin = '1970-01-01', tz = 'Europe/Berlin')`. For example, the nanoseconds in row 1 from the raw output is “2022-08-27 16:52:03 CEST” after conversion."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:602
msgid "For use with OSCAR, this date-time should then be converted to a character string with the date as DD.MM.YY followed by a comma. All of this can be achieved with one command (this operation can be vectorized over the entire column in the data frame); replace the YYYY-MM-DD date with the date of your measurements:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:604
msgid "`stringr::str_replace(as.character(as.POSIXct(1661611923019071/1000000, origin = '1970-01-01', tz = 'Europe/Berlin')), '2022-08-27', '27.08.22,')`"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:606
msgid "The output in Watts should be averaged per second. The same data above is shown below after processing with R; note the 7 values above are averaged per second, resulting in two rows."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:608
msgid "To save the CSV file with a semi-colon separator, the first column with row names starting at the number 1, and no string delimiter, use the following R command:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:610
msgid "`write.csv2(<DATAFRAME>, file = <PATH/TO/FILE.csv>, row.names = TRUE, quote = FALSE)`"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:612
msgid "The result should look something like the following:"
msgstr ""

