#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:816
msgid "Preparing The Documentation For Blue Angel"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:818
msgid "For Blue Angel eco-certification, it is necessary to complete several forms alongside the two reports from `OSCAR`."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:820
msgid "Information that needs to be included in the forms is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:822
msgid "Details about the software (name, version) and measurement process (when and where measurements were made, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:824
msgid "Technical details about the power meter (instrument, sampling frequency, length of scenario, sample size)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:826
msgid "Technical details about the reference system (year, model, processor, cores, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:828
msgid "Software stack used for the measurements (`xdotool`, `Collectl`, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:830
msgid "Minimum system requirements (processor architecture, local working memory, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:832
msgid "Energy consumption results found in the `OSCAR` reports or equivalent."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:834
msgid "Hardware utilization results, which includes the following (for IDLE use the idle mode measurements, and for SUS use the standard usage scenario measurements):"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:835
msgid "*Full Load*: “For processing power, the full load is 100%, for working memory the sum of the installed RAM capacities, for network bandwidth the maximum transmission speed, etc.” (Blue Angel award criteria: p. 23)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:836
msgid "*Base Load*: Average load for the reference system in Baseline measurements."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:837
msgid "*Idle/SUS Load*: Average load for the reference system for IDLE/SUS measurements."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:839
msgid "From the above measurements, the following calculations are made for hardware utilization (for IDLE use the idle mode measurements, and for SUS use the standard usage scenario measurements):"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:840
msgid "*Net Load*: IDLE/SUS Load - Base Load"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:841
msgid "*Allocation Factor*: Net Load/(Full Load - Base Load)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:842
msgid "*Effective Load*: Net Load + Allocation Factor * Base Load"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:843
msgid "*Hardware Utilization* (SUS only): Effective Load * Time (seconds)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:845
msgid "For Blue Angel eco-certification, the above information will be added to two documents called “Annex 1” and “Annex 2”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:849
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1043
msgid "[Annex 1](https://invent.kde.org/teams/eco/blue-angel-application/-/blob/master/applications/okular/de-uz-215-eng-annex-1-okular.docx)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:850
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1044
msgid "[Annex 2](https://invent.kde.org/teams/eco/blue-angel-application/-/blob/master/applications/okular/de-uz-215-eng-annex-2-okular.xlsx)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:852
msgid "<a name=\"sec:gosundPM\"></a> Alternative: Gosund SP111 Setup"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:854
msgid "Want to get started with the process of measuring your software, but short on cash or gear? Want to give the process a try without setting up a dedicated lab? Try this hack converting an inexpensive power plug to a power meter, courtesy of Volker Krause, who also documented the process provided here. You can read more at the following posts from Volker’s blog:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:856
msgid "[“*Cheap Electric Power Measurement*”](https://web.archive.org/web/20221002125057/https://volkerkrause.eu/2020/10/17/kde-cheap-power-measurement-tools.html)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:858
msgid "[“*KDE Eco Sprint July 2022*”](https://web.archive.org/web/20220819231538/https://www.volkerkrause.eu/2022/07/23/kde-eco-sprint-july-2022.html)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:860
msgid "Below is a guide to setting up a [Gosund SP111](https://templates.blakadder.com/gosund_SP111_v2.html) power plug already [flashed](https://github.com/tasmota/docs/blob/development/docs/devices/BlitzWolf-SHP6.md) with [Tasmota firmware](https://tasmota.github.io/docs) in 10 steps."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:862
msgid "Although the data from the inexpensive power meter will likely not be accepted by the Blue Angel for eco-certification, it is nonetheless possible to obtain preliminary data using this tool."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:864
msgid "(0) *Prerequisite*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:866
msgid "It is necessary to have the power plug already flashed with a sufficiently new Tasmota version."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:868
msgid "(1) *Firmware Reset*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:870
msgid "If the device had previously been connected to another Wifi network, it might need a full reset before being able to connect to a new one."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:872
msgid "If the device did open a WiFi access point named “tasmota-XXXXX” this is not needed, continue directly to (2)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:874
msgid "Press the button for 40 seconds."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:876
msgid "The device will restart and you should be able to continue at (2)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:878
msgid "(2) *WiFi Setup*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:880
msgid "The device opens a WiFi access point named “tasmota-XXXXX”&mdash;connect to that."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:882
msgid "Open http://192.168.4.1 in a browser."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:884
msgid "The device will ask you for the WiFi name and password to connect to after entering those. The device will reconnect to that WiFi and disable its access point."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:886
msgid "While doing that it should show you its new address in the browser&mdash;make a note of it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:888
msgid "In case that did not happen, check your WiFi router for the address of the device."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:890
msgid "(3) *Tasmota Setup*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:892
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:918
msgid "Open the address from step (2) in a browser."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:894
msgid "You should see the Tasmota web UI (a big “ON/OFF” text and a bunch of blue and one red button)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:896
msgid "Click “Configuration”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:898
msgid "Click “Configure Other”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:900
msgid "Copy"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:906
msgid "into the template input field."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:908
msgid "Tick the “Activate” checkbox."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:910
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:966
msgid "Click “Save”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:912
msgid "The device will restart; connect to it again."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:914
msgid "The UI should now also contain text fields showing electrical properties, and the “Toggle” button should now actually work."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:916
msgid "(4) *Calibration*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:920
msgid "Connect a purely resistive load with a known wattage, such as a conventional light bulb (not a LED or energy-saving bulb)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:922
msgid "Switch on power by clicking “Toggle” if needed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:924
msgid "Verify that the “Power Factor” value is shown as 1 (or very close to 1); if it is lower, the current load is not suited for calibration."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:926
msgid "Click “Console”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:928
msgid "Enter the following commands one at a time and press enter:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:938
msgid "Enter the command PowerSet XXX with XXX replaced by the wattage specified for the test load (e.g., “40” for a 40W light bulb)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:940
msgid "Click “Main Menu”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:942
msgid "The main page now should show correct power readings with several decimals precision."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:944
msgid "(5) *MQTT Broker Setup*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:946
msgid "At present, the only known way to achieve high-frequency automatic readouts is by polling over MQTT. This is not ideal and needs additional setup, unfortunately."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:948
msgid "If you happen to have a MQTT Broker around already, skip to step (6); otherwise, you need to set one up. The below scenario assumes Mosquitto is packaged for your GNU/Linux distribution (and therefore does not configure any security), so only do this in your own trusted network and switch it off when not needed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:950
msgid "install the `mosquitto` package"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:951
msgid "add a file `/etc/mosquitto/conf.d/listen.conf` with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:956
msgid "start Mosquitto using `systemctl start mosquitto.service`"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:958
msgid "(6) *MQTT Tasmota Setup*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:960
msgid "Connect to the Tasmota device using a web browser, and open the MQTT configuration page via Configuration > Configure MQTT."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:962
msgid "Enter the IP address of the MQTT broker into the “Host” field."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:964
msgid "Note down the value shown right of the “Topic” label in parentheses (typically something like “tasmota_xxxxxx”). This will be needed later on to address the device via MQTT. You can also change the default value to something easier to remember, but this has to be unique if you have multiple devices."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:968
msgid "The device will restart and once it is back you should see output in its Console prefixed with “MQT”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:970
msgid "(7) *Verifying MQTT Communication*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:972
msgid "This assumes you have the Mosquitto client tools installed, which are usually available as distribution packages."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:974
msgid "You need two terminals to verify that MQTT communication works as intended."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:976
msgid "In terminal 1, run `mosquitto_sub -t 'stat/<topic>/STATUS10'`"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:977
msgid "In terminal 2, run `mosquitto_pub -t 'cmnd/<topic>/STATUS' -m '10'`"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:979
msgid "Replace `<topic>` with the value noted down in step (6)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:981
msgid "Everytime you run the second command, you should see a set of values printed in the first terminal."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:983
msgid "(8) *Continuous Power Measurements*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:985
msgid "See [these scripts](https://volkerkrause.eu/2020/10/17/kde-cheap-power-measurement-tools.html)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:987
msgid "(9) *Switching WiFi Networks*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:989
msgid "For security reasons, once connected to a WiFi network, Tasmota will not let you get back to step (2) by default without hard resetting the device (40-second button press). However, a hard reset also removes all settings and the calibration. If you need to move to a different network, there are less drastic options available, but these changes can only be made inside the network you originally connected to:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:991
msgid "Under Configuration > Configure WiFi, you can add details for a second WiFi access point. Those will be tried alternatingly with the first configuration by default. This does not compromise security, but requires you to know the details for the network you want to connect to."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:993
msgid "You can configure Tasmota to open an access point as in step (2) by default for a minute or so after boot, and then try to connect to the known configurations. This makes booting slower in known networks, and opens the potential for hijacking the device, but it can be convenient when switching to unknown networks. This mode can be enabled in the Console by the command `WifiConfig 2`, and disabled by the command `WifiConfig 4`."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:995
msgid "For Tasmota version 11 the 40-second button press reset can leave the device in a non-booting state, whereas resetting from the Console using `Reset 1` doesn’t have that problem, but has to be done before disconnecting from the known WiFi as well."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:997
msgid "(10) *Recovering Non-Booting Devices*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:999
msgid "First and foremost: **DO NOT CONNECT THE DEVICE TO MAIN POWER**! That would be life-threatening. The entire flashing process is solely powered from 3.3V supplied by the serial adapter. Do not do any of this without having read this [getting started guide](https://tasmota.github.io/docs/Getting-Started/)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1001
msgid "With Tasmota 11, you can end up in a non-booting state by merely resetting the device using the 40-second button press. This does not permanently damage the device, and it can be fixed with reflashing via a serial adapter."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1003
msgid "The basic process is described in the above [guide](https://tasmota.github.io/docs/Getting-Started/). The PCB layout of the Gosund SP 111 can be seen [here](https://templates.blakadder.com/gosund_SP111_v1_1)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1005
msgid "In order for this to work, you need to connect GPIO0 (second pin on bottom left in the above image) to GND **before** powering up (i.e., before connecting with USB). The device LEDs (red and blue) are a useful indicator of whether you ended up in the right boot mode: the red LED should be on, and not flashing quickly, and the blue and red LED should not be on together. Once in that state, the connection can be removed (e.g., if you just hold a jumper cable to the pin) and it will remain in the right mode until a reboot."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1007
msgid "Again: **DO NOT CONNECT THE DEVICE TO MAIN POWER** as this is life-threatening."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1009
msgid "(B) Hardware Operating Life"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1011
msgid "The criteria in category (B) ensure that the software has low-enough performance requirements to run on older, less powerful hardware at least five years old."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1013
msgid "Many FOSS applications run on hardware much older than 5 years. In fact, members of the KDE community have noted that KDE’s desktop environment `Plasma` runs on hardware from even 2005!"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1015
msgid "This category is relatively easily to fulfill for the Blue Angel application. Compliance entails a declaration of backward compatibility, including details about the hardware on which the software runs and the required software stack. To demonstrate compliance, document the following information in two documents called “Annex 1” and “Annex 2”:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1017
msgid "*Reference System Year* &mdash; e.g., 2015"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1019
msgid "*Model* &mdash; e.g., Fujitsu Esprimo 920"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1021
msgid "*Processor* &mdash; e.g., Intel Core i5-4570"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1023
msgid "*Cores* &mdash; e.g., 4"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1025
msgid "*Clock Speed* &mdash; e.g., 3,6 GHz"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1027
msgid "*RAM* &mdash; e.g., 4 GB"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1029
msgid "*Hard Disk (SSD/HDD)* &mdash; e.g., 500 GB"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1031
msgid "*Graphics Card* &mdash; e.g., Intel Ivybridge Desktop"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1033
msgid "*Network* &mdash; e.g., Realtek Ethernet"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1035
msgid "*Cache* &mdash; e.g., 6144 KB"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1037
msgid "*Mainboard* &mdash; e.g., Fujitsu D3171-A1"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1039
msgid "*Operating System* &mdash; e.g., Ubuntu 18.04"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1041
msgid "Again, examples for Okular can be found at the following links:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1048
msgid "As discussed in PART II, the Blue Angel user autonomy criteria cover eight general areas:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/be4foss-handbook/handbook_web.md:1050
msgid "Data Formats"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
